nodes.bodyText:
Suggested solution: add a default ifExists(Class<B> otherClass, BiJoiner<A,B>... joiners); that callsifExists(Class otherClass, List joiners)`
default <B> UniConstraintStream<A> ifExists(Class<B> otherClass, BiJoiner<A, B>... joiners) {
    ifExists(otherClass, Arrays.asList(joiners));
}

<B>  UniConstraintStream<A> ifExists(Class<B> otherClass, List<BiJoiner<A, B>> joiners);

Cannot make an interface method final, which is a blocker for @SafeVarargs. If you want to use this suggestion, we have two options:

Turn the interfaces into abstract classes (which allow us to use final).
Create a static wrapper.
I think both of those options are bad.

If you allow @SuppressWarnings, there a third option:
public interface TestInterface<A> {

    default <B> List<A> myMethodVarargs(Class<B> otherClass, @SuppressWarnings("unchecked") A... data) {
        return myMethodList(otherClass, Arrays.asList(data));
    }

    <B> List<A> myMethodList(Class<B> otherClass, List<A> data);
}

Actually, thinking about this again, could you perhaps explain why you would need a method like that?
Personally I consider this:
   ifExists(Something.class, joiner1, joiner2, joiner3, joiner4);

To be much better than this:
   ifExists(Something.class, Arrays.asList(joiner1, joiner2, joiner3, joiner4));

But perhaps there is some aspect that I'm missing.

