nodes.bodyText:
Due to Lambda identity, I'd implement this slight different. Let me explain:
These 2 statements use the same lambda instance:

from(A.class).join(B.class).filter(Objects::equal)
from(A.class).join(B.class).filter(Objects::equal)

These 2 statements do NOT use the lambda instance:

from(C.class).join(D.class).filter((c, d) -> c.equals(d))
from(C.class).join(D.class).filter((c, d) -> c.equals(d))

You can try this out by printing System.systemHashCode() on those BiPredicates.
Now, why do we care about that? Because of node sharing in Drools AND Bavet.
If its the same lambda instance, node sharing work guaranteed.
If it isn't, Bavet won't see it and Drools has some dirty ASM magic that might or might not recognize they are the same code.
Unfortunately, there is no Objects.notEquals in java.util.Objects.
Apache commons-lang3 does have ObjectUtils.notEqual, presuming we want to use that, I would write:
return ifExists(otherClass, Joiners.filtering(ObjectUtils::notEqual);

